Step 3: Core Git Concepts (The Mental Model)

Working Directory: Where you edit files
Staging Area (Index): Files you prepare for commit (git add)
Repository (.git folder): Where commits are stored
Commit: A snapshot of your changes with a message
Branch: A parallel line of development (e.g., main, feature/login)
Remote: Usually GitHub/GitLab/Bitbucket (e.g., origin)

Step 4: Essential Git Commands (Start Here)
Initialize or Clone a Project
git init                  # Create new repo in current folder
git clone <url>           # Download existing repo (e.g., from GitHub)

Day-to-Day Workflow

git status                # See what's changed
git add file.txt          # Stage a file (or git add . for all)
git add -p                # Stage specific changes interactively (great habit!)
git commit -m "Add login form"   # Commit with message

View History

git log                   # Full history
git log --oneline --graph # Compact visual history OR git log --oneline
git diff                  # See unstaged changes
git show <commit-hash>    # See what a specific commit changed

Branching (One of Git's Superpowers)

git branch                # List branches
git switch -c feature/new-ui   # Create and switch to new branch (modern way)
# or older: git checkout -b feature/new-ui // switch(change) branch to master or master to branch
git delete -d  <branch_name>  // To delete branch  

git switch main           # Switch back to main
git merge <branch_name> # Merge your feature into main
Working with Remote (GitHub)

Create a repo on GitHub.com

Link your local repo:

git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/yourrepo.git

Push:

git push -u origin main

// enter usr name & pswd of github

Pull latest changes:

git pull origin main

